In TypeScript, you can use a union type to specify that a variable can have multiple values, but in practice it only has one value. Different types of objects and values can be assigned to variables of the same type, but in practice, a specific type is used.

```ts
type Person = {
  name: string,
  age: number
}
const person: Person = {
  name: 'John',
  age: 42
}
```
In this example, the type of person is a union type that contains two fields: name and age. However, the actual value of person is just an object with the name and age fields. This is known as "type inference" in TypeScript.

Here is an example of a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of times a specific word appears:

```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::ifstream input("input.txt");
    std::string word;
    int count = 0;

    while (input >> word) {
        if (word == "dog") {
            count++;
        }
    }

    std::cout << "The word 'dog' appears " << count << " times in the text file.";
}
```
